It's interesting how most heresies and heretics are just as "dogmatic" as orthodoxy (if not more), even if they flaunt an outward libertinism. Coincidentally, the least "dogmatism" (in the sense most people understand it) can be found in figures like St. Porphyrios or St. Paisios

People are taught by various Hollywood movies to imagine "dogma" as "an old man beating you on the head with a canon book", but this is precisely what happens in pretty much any pseudo-spiritual groups, Holy Mt. Athos' atmosphere is far less restrictive than a gnostic book club

Something interesting about St. Porphyrios I noticed is that he liked to give a "parable" with deep spiritual meaning, but later it turned out it was an actual anecdote that happened. He liked to work with reality, only seeking the symbolism between events that occur materially.

Like he told some students about a girl that every midnight sneaked out of her parents' house and crawled through thorns and bushes to secretly meet with a shepherd she loved, this as a metaphor for the Soul and Christ - turns out it was a real woman who confessed to him often.
"I was terrified at the unknowable roads that God's grace followed for the Salvation of people's souls"
